%I A395927 #31 May 18 2026 22:24:10
%S A395927 16,84,408,1764,6712,22672,68272,183472,436984,905776,1594648,2310264,
%T A395927 2644520,2250192,1260672,343184
%N A395927 a(n) is the number of different possible words of length n that can be found in a Boggle grid.
%C A395927 Boggle is a game played on a 4 X 4 grid, with each cell occupied by a letter. The player tries to make as many words, using a king's move self-avoiding walk. This sequence gives the number of possible words of length 1 to 16, irrespective of whether they are dictionary words, that can be found in the grid.
%C A395927 Also, the number of simple paths (aka self-avoiding walks) of length n on a 4 X 4 grid with king moves allowed.
%e A395927 a(1) = 16 since there are 16 positions on the 4 X 4 board.
%e A395927 a(2) = 84 since there are the following number of length-2 words arising from the king moves allowed when starting in each of the 16 board positions:
%e A395927   3 + 5 + 5 + 3;
%e A395927   5 + 8 + 8 + 5;
%e A395927   5 + 8 + 8 + 5;
%e A395927   3 + 5 + 5 + 3.
%e A395927 a(3) = 408, because there are 408 possible words of length three that can be found in a Boggle grid, arising from:
%e A395927   4 * (4 + 7 + 4) = 60 for the 4 corner positions;
%e A395927   8 * (2 + 4 + 7 + 7 + 4) = 8*(24) = 192 for the 8 side positions;
%e A395927   4 * (2 + 4 + 4 + 7 + 7 + 7 + 4 + 4) = 4*(39) = 156 for the 4 center positions.
%o A395927 (Python)
%o A395927 B = {(i, j) for i in range(4) for j in range(4)}
%o A395927 P = [(t,) for t in B]
%o A395927 for n in range(16):
%o A395927     print(len(P), end=", ")
%o A395927     P = [p+(q,) for p in P for i in range(-1, 2) for j in range(-1, 2) if (i or j) and (q:=(p[-1][0]+i, p[-1][1]+j)) in B and q not in p]
%o A395927 # _Michael S. Branicky_, May 12 2026
%K A395927 nonn,fini,full,walk,new
%O A395927 1,1
